I have s24 ultra and iphone 15 pro, and I noticed I like using s24 ultra more, the screen is so great for watching videos and reading ebooks, and the new AR coating is fantastic, it feels like reading a ereader.

Update on the S24 Ultra vs S25 Ultra

S24 Ultra
- Box Style shape (Just like the original note series)
- S24 Ultra first flat screen with eligant curved frame gives premium style (Flat screen protector frienldy)
- Brightness was tested as ive seen and notice is brighter. (Coating or what not probably causing this but the anti reflection is nearly identical)
- S-Pen bluetooth (Gimick or useful but still very nice knowing you have some inspector gadget type tech in your pocket if needed)
- One UI 7 Update for the S24U has some new video exporting blowing away the non optimized version of the S25 U as seen and tested.
- Camera rings are solid and premium (Flush no potential removal)
- 7 years of update (S24U) and was originally advertised as the AI phone already (I use all the AI features Minus the Now brief on the S25 Ultra i had it turned off)
- S-pen location on the S24 Ultra is in a perfect spot for cases (S25 Ultra seems to have it in a odd location where its curved so all the cases have a nasty open cutout in the corner)

S25 Ultra
- Feels like an Iphone which i always envyed iphone users having a flat square display but the samsung design lost its touch reminds me of the redmagic phone (not Note shape)
- Faster CPU but samsung is behind updating a more optimized version for the S25 Ultra
- Nearly only one year extra of uptades vs the S24 U 
- Extra pixels in one camera (I dont see the difference)
- Blue tooth 5.4 vs 5.3 (Dont notice much maybe the 6.0 will be a bigger upgrade.


Conclusion:
Sending my S25 Ultra back and will continue to use the S24 Ultra (I will snag a new one when they come back to the Note roots i have  under 7 years not in a hurry but ill cross my fingers on this one)

One thing I noticed is the battery management is absolutely amazing. Where I would run out 15% of my battery, I now run 1-2% max, it's actually insane...
Yes my S21 Ultra was getting old and I used it A LOT, so the battery would have been losing efficiency. But my god, that's 7x+ on the top end, I don't think i've ever had that experience when i've upgraded, and i've gone
S2 > S4 > S7 Edge > S9 Plus > S21 Ultra > Now this.
Not a single one of those upgrades gave me this battery efficiency.

Something everyone misses about screen saturation on the S24s is that by default the saturation slider is set to the lowest. Go into settings>display>adaptive colour tone and turn it off. Then go into screen mode, select "vivid" then the "advanced settings" button. You will get a 3 step slider. By default it is set to the lowest. I have mine in the middle. But if you like the old samsung overly saturated look, you can get it by sliding it to the max. The screen is amazing either way. And then you CAN turn adaptive colour tone back on.
The saturation problem was a bug. They added the vividness slider with an update and fixed it.

I have purchased Samsung phones exclusively since cell phones came on the scene. I mean, it powers down completely and the only way to access the phone is to turn it on and go through the power-on protocol. This means, I now must use my phone as a tablet, unless I am willing to go through the 2-3 minute power-on process each time I close the phone. I am passed warranty and repairs here in Mexico are somewhat problematic AND, how can you not have your phone for the days required for it to be repaired, a cost, I have been told, also appears to be steep... This comment is important.  DO NOT BUY ANY SAMSUNG DEVICE. Samsung updates will randomly give your device a green line. Do not listen to them saying it's damage, because I had multiple devices develop the line simultaneously,  no damage, some in box, and these are multiple generations of devices. The only common factor, an update. Samsung refuses to fix the issue, even denying they've had reports if thus, although there are hundreds of thousands facing this issue, if not more. There are reports on their own help forum, but they deny. You will be asked to return it to a Samsung repair center, if you live in a country that has these, and you will be charged a fee if your device is older than 1 year. This fee does not cover repairs. They will want to replace the screen, but the issue will eventually return because it's a software defect. I trust you know a new screen is almost the cost of the device. Note, even if you are in warranty,  you're not covered. Fingernail scratches are considered user damage, but tempered screen protectors are also considered damage because they use adhesive.  I have never seen that adhesive  damage a screen. Essentially,  they're damaging your device with an update you gave no choice in installing,  then will charge you to repair it. It is a cash grab that should face a class action  lawsuit.  Note that this is not based solely on my experience,rather, it is the common experience of those who encounter this problem and reach out to Samsung for help.

The Samsung Galaxy S24 Ultra outshines the iPhone 16 Pro Max in several key areas. First, the Galaxy S24 Ultra boasts a more advanced camera system. It features a 200-megapixel main sensor that provides unparalleled clarity and detail in photos, surpassing the iPhone's 48-megapixel main camera. Additionally, the Ultra's camera includes enhanced AI capabilities that significantly improve low-light photography and video stabilization, making it ideal for capturing high-quality content in any lighting condition.

Another significant advantage is the Galaxy S24 Ultra's battery life and charging technology. It comes equipped with a 5000mAh battery, which lasts longer than the iPhone 16 Pro Max's 4323mAh battery. Moreover, the Ultra supports super-fast charging, allowing you to charge up to 50% in just about 20 minutes. This is a considerable improvement over the iPhone, which charges more slowly. These features make the Galaxy S24 Ultra a more practical choice for users who need a powerful device that can keep up with their busy lifestyles.
